WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.440
So, thank you all for having me out today and joining me for my talk.

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:14.440
Again, my name is still Joe Kurinsic, and I'm here to talk to you all about scaling

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:18.120
your Shiny apps and some cool tools to do that.

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:22.600
But before we get into that, I'm going to talk about something a little different, which

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:25.360
is Rec League Sports.

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:30.240
In these low-stakes competitive arenas, there's a number of player archetypes that emerge.

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:34.799
But one that shows up often is the overextender.

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:37.599
This person is putting it all on the line on their team.

00:00:37.599 --> 00:00:42.080
They're doing everything, everywhere, all at once, and with an unrelenting fervor to

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:43.599
boot.

00:00:43.599 --> 00:00:44.680
We love this player.

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:46.240
We appreciate what they do.

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:51.279
But what becomes apparent very quickly is that they reach a point where they're doing

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:54.240
too much, and their performance just starts to get weird.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:56.360
It starts to lag.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:00.759
And it can get pretty weird at times.

00:01:00.759 --> 00:01:04.599
And truth be told, our Shiny apps are very much the same way.

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:10.239
You know, the process goes, you develop a prototype, you share it with a particular

00:01:10.239 --> 00:01:11.239
team.

00:01:11.239 --> 00:01:12.239
Team loves it.

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:13.300
Word starts getting around.

00:01:13.300 --> 00:01:16.360
Other teams begin to leverage your app as well.

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:18.720
Adoption continues to increase.

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:24.040
But you reach a certain critical mass where your Shiny app is serving a lot of these teams

00:01:24.599 --> 00:01:26.559
But the performance starts to lag.

00:01:26.559 --> 00:01:28.440
You know, the complaints start to roll in.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:30.320
My plots are lagging.

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:32.400
Or my report's taking too long to run.

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:35.760
Or you just get that spinning wheel of death that seems to be taking just a little too

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:38.559
long.

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:43.480
So this talk, okay, this talk is going to be a story about two things.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:50.199
One is going to be about a toy app that struggled to scale to a large number of users.

00:01:50.199 --> 00:01:56.360
And then we're also going to talk about how we use JavaScript to augment Shiny to overcome

00:01:56.360 --> 00:01:59.760
that struggle.

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:01.919
So this is the app that we start with.

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:07.239
It's a very simple Shiny application with two interactive hex bin plots.

00:02:07.239 --> 00:02:09.759
Simple easy and nice.

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:13.080
So with an app like this, you know, what seems to be the issue?

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:19.520
The issue happens when we go from one concurrent user, which is me operating this app locally,

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:27.720
to when we have 100 concurrent users accessing this app at the same time.

00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:32.240
And that problem is underscored by this plot that I'm going to show you all right here.

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:37.880
Now for some of you that aren't familiar with kind of like load testing tools for Shiny,

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:39.399
this plot may be a little bit opaque.

00:02:39.399 --> 00:02:41.440
So let's try to break it down a little bit.

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:43.759
So this is what's known as a session duration plot.

00:02:43.759 --> 00:02:50.639
And it's showing 100 simulated users using the Shiny app.

00:02:50.639 --> 00:02:57.279
The ticks along the Y axis are basically representing your simulated users as they go through the

00:02:57.279 --> 00:03:00.479
workflow on the previous slide.

00:03:00.479 --> 00:03:07.339
And then each of these segments that are stretching across the X axis, that's the amount of time

00:03:07.339 --> 00:03:12.520
that it took a particular step in that user's workflow.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:16.000
And then we have, it's a, sorry, it might be skinny for those in the back, but there's

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.880
a red line here that is kind of a reference point that indicates how long the total workflow

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:24.580
took for a single concurrent user.

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:28.759
And here, for this workflow, is about 93 seconds.

00:03:28.759 --> 00:03:32.880
So there's two things that stand out in this plot.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:39.039
One is that we're noticing some inconsistency in when our users are finishing the workflow.

00:03:39.039 --> 00:03:43.800
From a UX perspective, the same workflow should take people the same amount of time

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:45.919
if they're accessing the app at the same time.

00:03:45.919 --> 00:03:48.720
That's just fair.

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:53.360
Another thing to notice is that the amount of time that it's taking to go through this

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:57.119
workflow is, has gotten longer.

00:03:57.119 --> 00:04:02.279
And in the worst case, we're seeing that some users are finishing close to 150 seconds,

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:05.279
as opposed to the 93 seconds for the one user.

00:04:05.279 --> 00:04:07.800
There's no bueno.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:11.720
So we have this problem, why is it happening?

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:15.320
To understand why it's happening, we want to quickly just run through some basics about

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:17.279
how Shiny works.

00:04:17.279 --> 00:04:22.119
Whenever we update one of the dropdowns in those hex bin plots, the browser is going

00:04:22.119 --> 00:04:26.839
to send a signal over to R and say, hey, can you please generate another plot for me?

00:04:26.839 --> 00:04:29.200
And then R is going to be like, sure, buddy, I got you.

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:33.399
And it's going to generate another PNG, which then the browser goes to render.

00:04:33.399 --> 00:04:37.399
So we have this nice bidirectional communication going.

00:04:37.399 --> 00:04:42.559
And that's nice when you have just one user, like when you're developing locally and whatnot.

00:04:42.559 --> 00:04:49.720
But this becomes a problem when you have many browsers connecting to your app simultaneously.

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:54.239
Most of the time, when you have your Shiny app deployed, there's ultimately a single

00:04:54.239 --> 00:04:57.480
R process that's underlying that app.

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:02.239
And when all of these browsers are connecting to it, that single R process is doing the

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:07.000
brunt of the work to serve up your plots, tables, et cetera.

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:09.679
Now, R is a very fast language.

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:11.920
But R is still a single-threaded language.

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:16.899
And so because of that, every Shiny app out of the box is going to reach a certain critical

00:05:16.899 --> 00:05:21.600
point where the R process becomes saturated.

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:24.880
And it develops a backlog of requests that it has to mow through.

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:30.320
And that backlog is what causes that increase in the session duration that we saw in the

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:33.480
plot earlier.

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:36.079
So that's, you know, we have a sense for what the problem is.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:38.160
So what are we going to do about this?

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:41.959
Now, there's been plenty of talks about scaling Shiny.

00:05:41.959 --> 00:05:44.839
And there's a lot of good strategies that have come from those.

00:05:44.839 --> 00:05:47.200
We can cache different assets.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:48.200
That's a good idea.

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:50.420
We should be doing that, if we're not already.

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:56.279
There's also asynchronous operations, you know, writing out files, like large IOE-type

00:05:56.279 --> 00:05:57.279
stuff.

00:05:57.279 --> 00:05:58.559
But that's not what we're here to talk about.

00:05:58.559 --> 00:06:00.559
We're here to talk about something a little weirder.

00:06:00.559 --> 00:06:08.920
We're going to talk about using JavaScript to fix this problem.

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:12.959
So what's the, like, use JavaScript, what are we going to do?

00:06:12.959 --> 00:06:19.920
The big idea here is that we can scale our Shiny applications by taking work from that

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:25.940
R process, that R session, and moving it into the browser.

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:27.640
So what does that mean?

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:32.119
If we think back to this previous diagram where all of the browsers are hitting this

00:06:32.119 --> 00:06:36.519
R process at the same time, like, please give me a plot, please give me a plot, please give

00:06:36.519 --> 00:06:39.600
me a plot, we're going to handle it a little differently now.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:45.320
We're going to have R take the data set that's to be plotted, and we're going to have R kick

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:48.279
it out to every connecting browser.

00:06:48.279 --> 00:06:52.679
And then from there, the browser will become responsible for regenerating the plots as

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:54.440
you update those dropdowns.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:07:00.000
So it's all happening within those individual browsers.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.140
So that's the idea, cool, but how do we pull this off?

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:08.760
So much like we use R packages to accomplish different needs that we have, there's some

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:12.760
JavaScript libraries that we need to get the job done.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:13.760
And so we're going to need, what are we going to need?

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:18.119
We're going to need a data manipulation library, something to select columns, filter data,

00:07:18.119 --> 00:07:24.600
aggregate if needed, and then we're going to need a data visualization library as well.

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:29.119
So for the data manipulation library, I chose DuckDB Wasm.

00:07:29.119 --> 00:07:32.480
So you might be thinking, like, DuckDB Wasm, you know, like, what does all that mean?

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:37.559
Well, DuckDB, if you haven't heard already, it's a database, but it's not just any database.

00:07:37.559 --> 00:07:42.279
I think of DuckDB as, like, SQLite, but for analytics workloads.

00:07:42.279 --> 00:07:46.700
It's designed from the ground up to munch through the sort of queries that our shiny

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:50.380
apps love to send.

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:52.500
But then what's the Wasm part?

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:57.700
Wasm is a shorthand for something called WebAssembly, which you can roughly think of as, you know,

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:00.980
assembly but tailor-made for the browser.

00:08:00.980 --> 00:08:07.339
And if those are still kind of, like, opaque descriptors, the important thing about, to

00:08:07.339 --> 00:08:11.220
take away from this slide, is that the synthesis of these two technologies, you take DuckDB

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:15.179
and WebAssembly and you put that in the browser, you get stupid fast queries.

00:08:15.179 --> 00:08:21.179
You're not going to lose any speed in manipulating data and whatnot if we move to the browser,

00:08:21.179 --> 00:08:22.179
which is good.

00:08:22.179 --> 00:08:25.179
Sick, even.

00:08:25.179 --> 00:08:29.820
For data visualization, I chose, because there's a lot of different JavaScript libraries for

00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:33.979
visualizing data, so I chose something called Observable Plot.

00:08:33.979 --> 00:08:40.760
It's a project that's built on top of a more mature project called D3.js, which is known

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:45.679
for, you know, being able to create any sort of bespoke data visualization you could think

00:08:45.679 --> 00:08:46.679
of.

00:08:46.679 --> 00:08:51.799
Now, I ultimately chose this one as opposed to something like D3 for two reasons.

00:08:51.799 --> 00:08:55.440
One is that, look, I'm not really a JavaScript developer.

00:08:55.440 --> 00:09:00.320
Like, I'm an R developer primarily, and so I'd like for my JavaScript library to have

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:05.479
as, you know, like, I don't want it to have a very steep learning curve, right?

00:09:05.479 --> 00:09:10.859
So the nice thing about Observable Plot is that it's very similar in spirit to ggplot2.

00:09:10.859 --> 00:09:14.359
If we look at the code samples here, on the left we have, you know, some garden variety

00:09:14.359 --> 00:09:21.039
ggplot2 code in R, and on the right is the equivalent code using the Observable Plot

00:09:21.039 --> 00:09:22.039
API.

00:09:22.039 --> 00:09:27.119
And you can see that there's a lot of good similarities here, right?

00:09:27.119 --> 00:09:32.400
The whole idea being that in both cases, we have this plot that we're going to be composing

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:37.719
by mapping different, you know, attributes of our data set to different geomes that come

00:09:37.719 --> 00:09:44.919
together to build this final, you know, composition that's the plot that we're after.

00:09:44.919 --> 00:09:47.640
Sick, awesome.

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:51.280
So the other thing is that it is flexible and expressive.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:53.919
We all love ggplot2 here, right?

00:09:53.919 --> 00:09:59.679
We love how it doesn't limit us in its ability to create visualizations and whatnot.

00:09:59.679 --> 00:10:06.159
And I didn't want to lose that when I moved from R into the browser.

00:10:06.159 --> 00:10:12.260
What's fortunate is that Observable Plot has a very expressive API that makes it easy to

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:16.000
develop all the sorts of plots that we're used to making with ggplots.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.179
We can have our scatter plots.

00:10:18.179 --> 00:10:20.539
We can have our column charts.

00:10:20.539 --> 00:10:24.359
We can have our difference plots that are annotated every which way.

00:10:24.359 --> 00:10:28.840
And just recently, tool tips have made its way into the project.

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:37.239
So that adds another layer of interactivity that you can inject into your visualizations.

00:10:37.239 --> 00:10:42.260
So we're not going to lose anything there, which is cool.

00:10:42.260 --> 00:10:45.440
So we've refactored our app now, okay?

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:51.440
So now we're using DuckDB Wasm and Observable Plot under the hood, and this is what the

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:52.440
result is.

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:57.679
The main difference is that we hit this send button, and what that's doing is sending the

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:01.960
data set that's in R over into the browser.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:06.679
And then from there, these hex bin plots that you're seeing that get generated, this is

00:11:06.679 --> 00:11:09.039
all happening inside the browser now.

00:11:09.039 --> 00:11:14.539
R isn't doing that work.

00:11:14.539 --> 00:11:17.239
So we've made these changes.

00:11:17.239 --> 00:11:19.559
Did it do anything, right?

00:11:19.559 --> 00:11:25.080
Well, this is a story that has a happy ending, fortunately, so we did improve on things.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:29.880
And we're going to see that in a new session duration plot here.

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:33.799
So this is the one that we started with, with the first app, okay?

00:11:33.799 --> 00:11:38.840
And we noticed that we have our reference duration of 93 seconds, and a lot of users

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:40.479
are finishing well past that.

00:11:40.479 --> 00:11:41.479
We don't like that.

00:11:41.479 --> 00:11:42.479
That's not good.

00:11:42.479 --> 00:11:46.299
Well, here's where we're at now.

00:11:46.299 --> 00:11:48.739
You see this red line on the far side?

00:11:48.739 --> 00:11:52.919
That's that same reference duration, so that's 93 seconds, okay?

00:11:52.919 --> 00:11:54.299
So that's cool.

00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:57.419
But then it's kind of confusing, because what's all these, like, little tiny bars on the left-hand

00:11:57.419 --> 00:11:58.419
side?

00:11:58.419 --> 00:12:03.380
Well, the important thing is that those are basically the operations that are needed to

00:12:03.380 --> 00:12:08.059
do to kick the data out into each of the individual browsers.

00:12:08.059 --> 00:12:11.500
From there on in, everything's happening inside the browser.

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:16.619
So that line, that backlog of requests that forms when you just have, like, a typical

00:12:16.619 --> 00:12:21.340
Shiny app out of the box, that line's gone, because everyone's first in line inside of

00:12:21.340 --> 00:12:24.099
their own browser.

00:12:24.099 --> 00:12:29.219
So this has a number of nice properties for us, right?

00:12:29.219 --> 00:12:32.179
We've achieved upwards of a 40% speed improvement.

00:12:32.179 --> 00:12:36.260
If you consider that in the worst case, users were finishing close to about 150 seconds

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:40.619
before, we've brought that back down to 93 seconds, which is good.

00:12:40.619 --> 00:12:41.820
Very good.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:47.320
We've also achieved consistency, because now that all of this is happening in the browser,

00:12:47.320 --> 00:12:50.780
everyone's going to be finishing their workflow in around the same time.

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:54.700
And again, we're talking about going from one to a hundred users, and now everybody's

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:59.219
finishing in around the same time, with relatively, you know, small changes to the code base.

00:12:59.219 --> 00:13:02.140
This is good stuff.

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:05.340
So that's nice.

00:13:05.340 --> 00:13:08.780
We get the consistent UX, yeah, that's true, and then we do get that dollop of dopamine

00:13:08.780 --> 00:13:12.340
that you feel, you know, when you do a good job, right?

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:16.099
You deliver on what you said you would, that's cool.

00:13:16.099 --> 00:13:19.859
So we've already talked a little bit about why this is awesome, but to kind of, like,

00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:21.299
put a bow on it, right?

00:13:21.299 --> 00:13:24.820
One thing that we've done is we've found a way to clear the prototype purgatory hurdle,

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:25.820
right?

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:27.700
And we all know what this is as Shiny developers.

00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:32.140
You build an app, it's great, people like using it, but then there's this does it scale

00:13:32.140 --> 00:13:34.900
question and stuff like that that we all have to deal with.

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:39.619
Well, this is a nice solution to that.

00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:42.940
In the case here, we were able to successfully scale to a hundred users.

00:13:42.940 --> 00:13:46.739
But there's another thing that I haven't really touched on yet, which is reduced infrastructure

00:13:46.739 --> 00:13:47.739
costs.

00:13:47.739 --> 00:13:48.940
And so what do I mean by that?

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:53.780
So a lot of the times when we want to scale Shiny applications, what happens is that we

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:57.900
usually resort to horizontal scaling, is what you call it, right?

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:02.260
Which basically you have your app, and then you make, you know, however many copies of

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:06.119
it, and then you load balance across each instance of that application.

00:14:06.119 --> 00:14:11.619
And that is a good strategy, it works, but the consequence is that it usually involves

00:14:11.619 --> 00:14:17.280
increased costs on your end to spin up all that extra compute.

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:21.679
We don't have to do that here, because we're making strategic use of all the connecting

00:14:21.679 --> 00:14:25.400
browsers that are visiting our application, which is sick.

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:26.880
I like that.

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:30.320
So this is all awesome.

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:31.320
All well and good.

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:33.940
But there's caveats, right?

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:36.479
So there's always going to be caveats.

00:14:36.479 --> 00:14:42.640
First is that if you're going to use a strategy like this, browsers are not servers.

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:43.799
Don't use them like that.

00:14:43.799 --> 00:14:48.039
If you start hucking petabytes of data at people's browsers, you're going to crash them

00:14:48.039 --> 00:14:49.919
and they're going to be mad at you.

00:14:49.919 --> 00:14:52.760
So maybe don't do that.

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:57.440
Another thing is that security still matters, especially if you're in the healthcare space

00:14:57.440 --> 00:15:00.320
or anything else that has, you know, sensitive data and things like that.

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:04.840
You don't want to necessarily just be throwing data and exposing it out in the browser where

00:15:04.840 --> 00:15:06.799
bad people can do bad things with it.

00:15:06.799 --> 00:15:09.799
That's not cool.

00:15:09.799 --> 00:15:14.359
And then another is that right now, so, like, this does have some minor hackery that I did

00:15:14.359 --> 00:15:15.359
to get this done.

00:15:15.359 --> 00:15:21.119
I have a link to the GitHub repo where this is where you can find this guy at.

00:15:21.119 --> 00:15:26.960
It's mostly just, like, minor changes to the HTTP UV package, just, like, adds a MIME type

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:29.599
for it to accept WASM files and stuff like that.

00:15:29.599 --> 00:15:34.679
But it's still kind of annoying to set up up front.

00:15:34.679 --> 00:15:38.080
But those are really much the only caveats I have.

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:39.359
Go ahead and try it.

00:15:39.919 --> 00:15:40.919
It's fun.

00:15:40.919 --> 00:15:43.039
And then let me know what you think.

00:15:43.039 --> 00:15:46.320
Those are my contact details, if you'd like to talk to me more about this kind of stuff

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:48.599
or other data-related things.

00:15:48.599 --> 00:15:52.280
And then there's the link to the GitHub repo as well.

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:53.960
But that's all I have for you guys.

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:56.960
Thanks again for joining me.

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:07.919
We have time for a couple of questions for Joe.

00:16:07.919 --> 00:16:11.479
The first one is kind of a cheeky question.

00:16:11.479 --> 00:16:17.000
Once you're using JS libraries, DuckDB, and WASM, what value is Shiny still providing

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:21.039
as a web framework over something like React?

00:16:21.039 --> 00:16:22.640
So I love that question, right?

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:30.880
So I think that what a strategy like this shows is that with all of these technologies,

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:34.159
it's important to start thinking about the strategy behind your application.

00:16:34.159 --> 00:16:38.000
A lot of the ideas that I brought up, like, browsers aren't servers and stuff like that.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.960
That's part of the thing that I would respond to with why I still think that some things

00:16:41.960 --> 00:16:44.599
should still be happening on the R side.

00:16:44.599 --> 00:16:49.840
Certain data manipulation and things like that may need to stay on-prem or in your own

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:53.320
servers and stuff like that, not happening in the browser.

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:55.640
And there's other reasons we could talk about, too.

00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:59.440
But I think that it's more like, we're not looking to replace one thing outright with

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:00.440
the other.

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:05.920
It's a good strategic tool to have in your belt.

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:06.920
Your next question.

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:10.880
Did you measure how long does it take to render on the client?

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:13.680
And can you share how large your data set was?

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:14.680
Yeah.

00:17:15.479 --> 00:17:20.839
I'd have to, so as far as how long it took to render the plots, since it's all happening

00:17:20.839 --> 00:17:26.599
inside the browser, if we, and I could just jump back to the slide real fast, so how long

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:31.800
it took to see the refactored app generate the plots, that's how fast it's going to be.

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:33.839
Because it's all happening in individual browsers.

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:36.479
There's no more competing for a single process.

00:17:36.479 --> 00:17:45.119
As far as how big the data set was, here it was about 56k rows, I believe.

00:17:45.119 --> 00:17:49.760
It's like 50s, yes.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:54.920
And your last question is, are there caveats to keep in mind when working with different

00:17:54.920 --> 00:17:57.800
browsers?

00:17:57.800 --> 00:17:58.800
Almost certainly.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:00.400
But I'm not smart enough to speak to that.

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:01.400
I'm sorry.

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:02.400
Yeah.

00:18:03.400 --> 00:18:06.400
Thank you, Joe.

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:10.400
I'm not the guy, unfortunately.

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:11.400
Thank you, Joe.

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:12.400
Thank you.

